<img src='https://www.gmbinder.com/images/tPFTqoe.png' style='position:absolute; top:100px; right:0px; width:400px' />

\pagebreakNum

### Affiliation
Orcs are members of the Horde and it would not exist with&shy;out them. They forged the Orcish Horde prior to the First War and the New Horde—also known as the Horde—during the Third War as the orcs made a lasting bond with races native to the continent of Kalimdor. Much of the Horde continues to be influenced by orcish culture and laws.

Although most orcs are members of the Horde, there are those who chose to isolate themselves from its influence and affiliated races. These reclusive clans are rarely friendly towards the Horde or its races and some show open hostility.

### Orc Names and Clans
Most orcish names derive from words in their language that have some complex meaning or hidden significance to their families. Typically, this is the name of a favorite thing or relative. Family names don’t exist; most orcs have last names related to some great deed of heroism or honor.

Orcs typically form into similarly minded groups known as clans. Each clan is lead by a chieftain and the leader of all clans is known as the Warchief, a title given to the leader of the current Horde. Some clans are ancestral and well-established, while others were established relatively recently by specific people for a specific purpose. In the latter case, loyalty is typically only held to the clan leader; once they die, the clan disperses.

The clan system has largely been abolished during the reign of Thrall as the Warchief in favor of a single Horde. Still, there are some who proudly bear the name of ancient clans or follow their ways. Below are seven orc clans who have been major players in the history of both Azeroth and Draenor, though many more exist.
<div style='margin-top:-18px;'></div>

<br>**Male Names:** Grom, Thrum, Drog, Gorrum, Harg, Thurg, <br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Karg, Regg, Kavenk, Uketel, Thrarturg, Crurn
<br>**Female Names:** Groma, Hargu, Igrim, Agra, Dragga, <br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Grima, Fehmo, Mohma, Sherge, Zuri, Orgis
<br>**Deed Names:** Cravensmile, Steelflame, Twinthunder, <br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Gravepride, Aridfire, Coldbrass, Foebinder, Elfkiller

#### Blackrock
The Blackrock are a disciplined, organized, 
<br/> and militaristic clan who boast expert smiths 
<br/> and metalworkers who utilize the tough ore 
<br/> from which they share their name. The 
<br/> Blackrock shamans used elemental forges 
<br/> and were among the first to descend into 
<br/> using fel magic.

Blackrock orcs typically have gray-hued skin from their time living under mountains. Male orcs of the Blackrock Clan never cut their hair until they come of age, at which point their head is shaved and their role in this extremely regimented society is determined.

The Blackrocks follow the ways of either a mystic or warrior clan.

\columnbreak

#### Bleeding Hollow
The Bleeding Hollow gain their name from the 
<br/> ritual performed by their chieftains and elders, 
<br/> where they ritualistically gouge out an eye in 
<br/> exchange for visions of the future, often of the 
<br/> time of their death. 

Hailing from the jungles of old Draenor, they 
<br/> imbue themselves with berserk fury, slather their 
<br/> weapons in hallucinogenic venom, and stalk prey from the treetops, branding their victims' final moments with visions of pure horror.

The orcs of the Bleeding Hollow follow the ways of the hunter and mystic clans.

#### Frostwolf
The Frostwolves are known for two things: their 
<br/> prowess in single combat and their close bonds 
<br/> with the wolves with which they share their 
<br/> name. Though smaller than many other orc clans, 
<br/> it is from them that the Warchief of the Horde 
<br/> known as Thrall was descended. 

No two creatures will share a stronger relation-
<br/>ship than that of a Frostwolf orc and his or her 
<br/> companion wolf. The two eat, sleep, and fight side by 
<br/> side until one or both dies an honorable death. Even 
<br/> then, sometimes not even death itself can stop a frostwolf from coming to the aid of its beloved orc.

The Frostwolves follow the ways of hunter and warrior clans.

#### Shadowmoon
These highly spiritual and shamanistic orcs 
<br/> come from Shadowmoon Valley in old Draenor, 
<br/> whose magic was derived from the moon, earth,
<br/> and stars. Considered to be the first shamans, a key 
<br/> source of their power was their understanding of
<br/> the movements of the stars and their omens. Their 
<br/> skin was often marked with bone-white tattoos and
<br/> secret runes used to enhance their connections to the elements and their ancestors.

Despite these peaceful origins, it was the Shadowmoon chieftain Ner'zhul who led the orcs in the second invasion of Azeroth, who created so many portals on Draenor that the planet was shattered into the broken Outland, and whose spirit was twisted by the demon Kil'jaeden into becoming the Lich King. Due to his actions, very few Shadowmoon orcs remain.

Orcs of the Shadowmoon clan almost exclusively follow the path of a mystic clan.

#### Shattered Hand
A relatively recently formed clan, this 
<br/> group of outcasts and former gladiator 
<br/> slaves gained their name both from how the 
<br/> slaves escaped their cuffs and from the self-
<br/> mutilation practices they sometimes perform 
<br/> in honor of it. They were known for being 
<br/> vicious warriors with a need to inflict pain on others.

Most of those who remained on Draenor when it was shattered into Outland were corrupted further into the demonic Fel Orcs, with their chieftain Kargath Bladefist becoming the Warchief of this new Fel Horde. Those few who were trapped in Azeroth eventually formed the Order of the Shattered Hand (or just "the Hand"), a multi-racial organization of spies and assassins working for the new Horde under Thrall.

The Shattered Hand follow the ways of all clans.

<img src='https://www.gmbinder.com/images/4JIFFWR.png' style='position:absolute; top:660px; left:290px; width:125px' /> <!-- Icon of the Blackrock Clan -->
<img src='https://www.gmbinder.com/images/76hRPzp.png' style='position:absolute; top:35px; right:0px; width:130px' /> <!-- Icon of the Bleeding Hollow Clan -->
<img src='https://www.gmbinder.com/images/rBsVY8r.png' style='position:absolute; top:235px; right:-8px; width:130px' /> <!-- Icon of the Frostwolf Clan -->
<img src='https://www.gmbinder.com/images/2tRvXMz.png' style='position:absolute; top:470px; right:-6px; width:135px' /> <!-- Icon of the Shadowmoon Clan -->
<img src='https://www.gmbinder.com/images/TtEPYSD.png' style='position:absolute; top:770px; right:15px; width:140px' /> <!-- Icon of the Shattered Hand Clan -->

\pagebreakNum

#### Thunderlord
Formed over 800 years ago, this clan gains its 
<br/> name from an ancient chieftain who single-
<br/> handedly defeated a giant at the pinnacle 
<br/> of Thunder Peak. This clan is famous not 
<br/> for their actions during the invasions of 
<br/> Azeroth, but for being near peerless hunters 
<br/> and masters of beasts.

Unlike the Frostwolves and similar clans, the Thunderlords sought to dominate the land instead of adapting to it. They used riding wolves, rylak air support, and clefthoof beasts of burden to great effect, specializing in group tactics and coordinated assaults to take down larger prey. However this focus tended to leave them individually weak and few remain today.

Thunderlords are quintessential examples of a hunter clan.

#### Warsong
The orcs of the Warsong clan were among 
<br/> the most feared warriors of Draenor and 
<br/> have played major roles in nearly every 
<br/> version of the Horde. Their name comes from 
<br/> their fearsome battle cries, the great war 
<br/> drums they march to, and the holes carved into 
<br/> their weapons that caused them to whistle and wail 
<br/> when swung through the air.

One of their most famous figures was Grommash "Grom" Hellscream, the first orc who drank the blood of the powerful demon Mannoroth the Destructor, which infected the orcs with his demonic taint. Grommash was a legendary warrior and chieftain, as well as mentor and chief lieutenant to Thrall during the Third War. Ultimately Grom would give his life to defeat Mannoroth, freeing the orcs from their enslavement to the Burning Legion.

The Warsong clan are perhaps some of the greatest examples of an orc warrior clan.

### Orc Traits
Your orc character has the following racial traits.

***Creature Type.*** You are a Humanoid. You are also considered an orc for any prerequisite or effect that requires you to be an orc.

***Ability Score Increase.*** Your Strength score increases by 1, and your Constitution score increases by 1.

***Age.*** Orcs mature a little faster than humans, reaching adulthood around age 14. They age noticeably faster and rarely live longer than 75 years.

***Alignment.*** Orcs might not have an innate tendency toward evil, but many end up there. Evil or not, many orcs lean toward a chaotic alignment.

***Size.*** Orcs are between 6 and 7 feet tall and muscularly built, averaging around 300 pounds. Your size is Medium. 

***Speed.*** Your base walking speed is 30 feet. 

***Hardiness.*** You have advantage on saves against being stunned or exhausted.

***Relentless Endurance.*** When you are reduced to 0 hit points but not killed, you can drop to 1 hit point instead. You must then finish a long rest to use this feature again.

***Savage Attacks.*** When you score a critical hit with a melee weapon attack, you can roll one of the weapon's damage dice one additional time and add it to the extra damage of the critical hit.

***Languages.*** You can speak, read, and write Common and Orcish. Orcish is a harsh, grating language with hard consonants. It has no script of its own but is written in a mix of dwarven runes and common.

***Clans.*** Orcs are taught different skills depending on their clan. Orcish clans are categorized into three: hunter clans, mystic clans, and warrior clans. Choose one of these clans and work with your DM to determine the significance of your chosen clan.

#### Hunter Clans
Some orc clans prefer a more stealth approach to things, hiding and waiting for the perfect time to ambush, such as the Shattered Hand clan, and the Bleeding Hollow clan. 

***Ability Score Increase.*** Your Dexterity score <br> increases by 1.

***Ambusher.*** You gain proficiency in the Perception and Stealth skills.

***Surprise Attack.*** If you hit a creature with an attack roll, the creature takes an extra 2d6 damage if it hasn't taken a turn yet in the current combat.

#### Mystic Clans
Not many orc clans go in for the use of magic, and those that do are usually more secretive than the rest. Generally less keen on working with other clans are spend their time as a nomadic folk rather than settling in a certain area. Such clans include The Shadowmoon, and Stormreaver. 

***Ability Score Increase.*** Your choice of your Intelligence or Wisdom score increases by 1.

***Ancestral Call.*** You know the *guidance* cantrip. Starting at 3rd level, you can cast the *heroism* spell with this trait. Starting 5th level, you can also cast the *augury* spell with this trait, without requiring a material component.

Once you cast *heroism* or *augury* with this trait, you can't cast that spell with it again until you finish a long rest. You can also cast either of those spells using any spell slots you have of the appropriate level. Intelligence, Wisdom, or Charisma is your spellcasting ability for these spells when you cast them with this trait (choose when you select this race).

***Mystic Lore.*** You are proficient with the following skills: Medicine and Nature.

#### Warrior Clans
Most known orc clans go for the brute forced approach, entering combat gladly with raised weapons, hammering down everything in their way. Some of the larger clans include Warsong, Burning Blade, and the Frostwolves. 

***Ability Score Increase.*** Your Strength score <br> increases by 1.

***Adrenaline Rush.*** You can take the Dash action as a bonus action. You can use this trait a number of times equal to your proficiency bonus, and you regain all expended uses when you finish a long rest.

Whenever you use this trait, you gain a number of temporary hit points equal to your proficiency bonus.

***Intimidating Stature.*** You gain proficiency in the Athletics and Intimidation skills.

<img src='https://www.gmbinder.com/images/mPPx1bF.png' style='position:absolute; top:40px; left:283px; width:140px' /> <!-- Icon of the Thunderlord Clan -->
<img src='https://www.gmbinder.com/images/B7KiCAd.png' style='position:absolute; top:300px; left:290px; width:130px' /> <!-- Icon of the Warsong Clan -->

