<br/> elders, where they ritualistically gouge out 
<br/> an eye in exchange for visions of the future, 
<br/> often of the time of their death. 

Hailing from the jungles of old Draenor, they 
<br/> imbue themselves with berserk fury, slather their 
<br/> weapons in hallucinogenic venom, and stalk prey from the treetops, branding their victims' final moments with visions of pure horror.

The orcs of the Bleeding Hollow follow the ways of the hunter and mystic clans.

#### Frostwolf
The Frostwolves are known for two things: 
<br/> their prowess in single combat and their 
<br/> close bonds with the wolves with which they 
<br/> share their name. Though smaller than many 
<br/> other orc clans, it is from them that the 
<br/> Warchief of the Horde known as Thrall 
<br/> was descended. 

No two creatures will share a stronger relation-
<br/>ship than that of a Frostwolf orc and his or her 
<br/> companion wolf. The two eat, sleep, and fight side by 
<br/> side until one or both dies an honorable death. Even 
<br/> then, sometimes not even death itself can stop a frostwolf from coming to the aid of its beloved orc.

The Frostwolves follow the ways of hunter and warrior clans.

#### Shadowmoon
These highly spiritual and shamanistic 
<br/> orcs come from Shadowmoon Valley in old 
<br/> Draenor, whose magic was derived from the 
<br/> moon, earth, and stars. Considered to be the 
<br/> first shamans, a key source of their power was 
<br/> their understanding of the movements of the 
<br/> stars and their omens. Their skin was often marked with bone-white tattoos and secret runes used to enhance their connections to the elements and their ancestors.

Despite these peaceful origins, it was the Shadowmoon chieftain Ner'zhul who led the orcs in the second invasion of Azeroth, who created so many portals on Draenor that the planet was shattered into the broken Outland, and whose spirit was twisted by the demon Kil'jaeden into becoming the Lich King. Due to his actions, very few Shadowmoon orcs remain.

Orcs of the Shadowmoon clan almost exclusively follow the path of a mystic clan.

#### Shattered Hand
A relatively recently formed clan, this 
<br/> group of outcasts and former gladiator 
<br/> slaves gained their name both from how the 
<br/> slaves escaped their cuffs and from the self-
<br/> mutilation practices they sometimes perform 
<br/> in honor of it. They were known for being 
<br/> vicious warriors with a need to inflict pain on others.

Most of those who remained on Draenor when it was shattered into Outland were corrupted further into the demonic Fel Orcs, with their chieftain Kargath Bladefist becoming the Warchief of this new Fel Horde. Those few who were trapped in Azeroth eventually formed the Order of the Shattered Hand (or just "the Hand"), a multi-racial organization of spies and assassins working for the new Horde under Thrall.

The Shattered Hand follow the ways of all clans.

#### Thunderlord
Formed over 800 years ago, this clan gains its 
<br/> name from an ancient chieftain who single-
<br/> handedly defeated a giant at the pinnacle 
<br/> of Thunder Peak. This clan is famous not 
<br/> for their actions during the invasions of 
<br/> Azeroth, but for being near peerless hunters 
<br/> and masters of beasts.

Unlike the Frostwolves and similar clans, the Thunderlords sought to dominate the land instead of adapting to it. They used riding wolves, rylak air support, and clefthoof beasts of burden to great effect, specializing in group tactics and coordinated assaults to take down larger prey. However this focus tended to leave them individually weak and few remain today.

Thunderlords are quintessential examples of a hunter clan.

#### Warsong
The orcs of the Warsong clan were among 
<br/> the most feared warriors of Draenor and 
<br/> have played major roles in nearly every 
<br/> version of the Horde. Their name comes from 
<br/> their fearsome battle cries, the great war 
<br/> drums they march to, and the holes carved into 
<br/> their weapons that caused them to whistle and 
<br/> wail when swung through the air.

One of their most famous figures was Grommash "Grom" Hellscream, the first orc who drank the blood of the powerful demon Mannoroth the Destructor, which infected the orcs with his demonic taint. Grommash was a legendary warrior and chieftain, as well as mentor and chief lieutenant to Thrall during the Third War. Ultimately Grom would give his life to defeat Mannoroth, freeing the orcs from their enslavement to the Burning Legion.

The Warsong clan are perhaps some of the greatest examples of an orc warrior clan.

